\szakasz[Minkowski distance]{Minkowski distance}

\begin{frame}[t]

We are looking for an observer-independent distance events.

\[
\mu (e,e')\defegy 
\begin{array}{l}
x & \textup{ if an inertial observer through $e$ and $e'$ measures the elapsed time between $e$ and $e'$ to be $x$}
0 & \textup{ if there is a photon through $e$ and $e'$.}
-x & \textup{ if an inertial observer according to whom $e$ and $e'$ are simultaneous, the spatial distance between $e$ and $e'$ is $x$.}
\end{array}\]

So every observer has its own jurisdiction, so no matter which observer you ask, they will direct you to the one who is allowed to answer that question. Therefore this notion is observer-independent. Also, the Minkowski distance of $e$ and $e'$ according to $k$ happens to be
\[ \mu_k (e,e') = \sqrt{(e_t-e'_t)^2- (e_x-e'_x)^2- (e_y-e'_y)^2- (e_z-e'_z)^2} \]
\end{frame}
